column2: Local partners effectively respond to Child Protection risks among new arrivals appropriate to their age, gender, and disability.

Activity3.1: Support the identification, registration and assessment of Children at Risk (CAR) to access child protection services - case management, cash support and referrals - through the existing Child Protection structures
Provide appropriate case management support through documentation and reporting of cases (Nakivale 1350, Nyakabande 2000)
Enhance case reporting through promoting referral mechanisms and establishing child friendly reporting procedures.
Trainings and conduct case conferencing for child protection cases and provide durable solutions.
Training for staff on Best Interest Procedure (BIP) alternative care framework by MGLSD and Progress V4
Conduct child family tracing and reunification

Activity3.2: Provide emergency support to Children at Risk (CAR) and their caregivers including Basic Food items, Core Relief Items (CRI) and Non-Food Items (NFIs) at the reception and transit centres.
Case Management & referrals to service providers - Provide Individual Protection Assistance to children like blankets, sleeping mats, clothes.etc

Activity3.3: Support community-level Child Protection with a nexus lens through training and mentorship of community-level actors and structures to effectively deliver safe, age-appropriate and sustainable child protection activities in refugee settlements and transit centres and through CP messaging.
Capacity strengthening, training and mentorship of community structures on Inter-agency Standing Committee (IASC) guidelines for case management and child protection.
Children with CP concerns Identified at community-level by Parasocial workers, shelter leaders, community leaders
Procure and distribute IEC materials, visibility materials. (Frequency)

Activity3.4: Enhance caregivers and family support initiatives using the Be There and Parenting without violence approaches, while linking caregivers with available livelihood, skilling and market-oriented opportunities.
Sensitize parents, caregivers, and community members on  the prevention of abuse and neglect of children (Be there and parenting without violence)
Provide material support to foster parents and care givers
Activtiy3.5: Engage children and their caregivers in both environmental conservation and climate education.
Conduct Interactive Sessions with Children on Rights and Responsibility, adoption of environment friendly practices.
Acitivtiy3.6: Strengthen existing community-based Child Protection systems to effectively manage child protection cases and act for children at risk and in need of urgent support.
Establish and / or maintain child friendly spaces
Operationalize child friendly spaces and train and facilitate ECD caregivers and support peer-to-peer group activities at the CFS
Provide learning or training materials and stationaries including art books, charts, pencils, crayons, etc. (frequency)

Government staff (including Probation and Welfare Officer, Sub County CDO
and OPM) members of CPCs at community-level trained on CP and supported to attend monthly meetings
